{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ab72bf25-362d-421c-b732-7e87e0b4b415","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, but here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish as a **dotnet tool** on NuGet.org:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageProjectUrl>https://github.com/you/MyMcpServer</PackageProjectUrl>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n| Property | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `PackAsTool` | Marks the project as a .NET tool |\n| `ToolCommandName` | The CLI command users will run |\n| `OutputType=Exe` | Required — tools must be executables |\n\n### Publish steps\n\n```bash\n# 1. Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# 2. Push to NuGet.org (get API key from nuget.org/account/apikeys)\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install & run with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server          # runs via stdio\n```\n\nThat's the minimal setup — `PackAsTool` + `ToolCommandName` are the two critical properties that distinguish a dotnet tool from a regular NuGet package.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3eba1488-2aa3-4757-bf0f-1cba43079ae2","outputTokens":469,"requestId":"CC29:307F5D:821D135:906C36E:69EAC232"},"id":"055e97ed-a1a1-4097-9a36-059528014b5a","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:07:07.661Z","parentId":"402e2815-cc70-43f7-9e76-9e21e675b8f6"}
